Letting n -> infinity in the above series for a(n) given by Kotesovec gives the series expansion 1/e^2 = Sum_{k >= 0} (-1)^k*(k + 3)*2^(k + 3)/(k + 5)!.

The sequence b(n) := 1/2*n!*(n + 2)*(n + 5) satisfies the recurrence for a(n) given above by Pauly but with the starting values b(0) = 5 and b(1) = 9. a(n) = U(1/2, n+3/2, 1/4)/2 where U denotes the Kummer U function. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 26 2014

a(n+k) = a(n) (mod k) for all n and k. It follows that the sequence a(n) taken modulo k is periodic with the exact period dividing k. For example, modulo 10 the sequence becomes 1, 3, 7, 3, 1, 1, 3, 7, 3, 1, ... with exact period 5.
The e.g.f. A(x) = 1/sqrt(1 - 4*x)*exp(x) satisfies the differential equation (1 - 4*x)A' - (3 - 4*x)*A = 0 with A(0) = 1. Mathar's recurrence above follows from this. (End)

formula: If p[i] = Stirling1(i,1) and if A is the Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by A[i,j] = p[j-i+1], (i <= j), A[i,j] = -1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise, then, for n >= 1, a(n-1) = (-1)^(n-1) det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 08 2010

a(n) = binomial(3*n+1, n) + binomial(3*n, n-1) for n>=0. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 22 2013
G.f.: G(x)*(2*G(x) - 1) / (3 - 2*G(x)), where G(x) = 1 + x*G(x)^3 is the g.f. of A001764. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 22 2013

formula: Expansion of 2 * q^(1/4) * ((k'^4 + 4*k^2) / (k'^2 * k))^(1/2) in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 01 2014
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = A(q^4) / q satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^3)) where f(u, v) = (u^2 + v^2)^2 - (u*v - 12) * (u*v - 32)^2. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 01 2014

Convolution square is A007247. Convolution fourth power is A007267.

formula: a(0)=0, a(n) = n*10^len(a(n-1)) + a(n-1), where len(k) = number of digits in k and len(0)=1; = A000422*10.

A052271.name: Number of n X n matrices over GF(4) under row and column permutations.

A052272.name: Number of n X n matrices over GF(5) under row and column permutations.

formula: Conjecture: a(2^e) = 1+floor[2^e/(2^4-1)] if e ==0 (mod 4). a(2^e) = 2+floor[2^e/(2^4-1)] if e == {1,2,3} mod 4. - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 22 2017

A052274.name: Number of distinct 5th powers mod n.
formula: Conjecture: a(p^e) = 1+floor[(p-1)*p^(e+4)/{gcd(p-1,5)*(p^5-1)}] for primes p<>5  - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 22 2017

A052275.name: Number of distinct 6th powers mod n.

formula: a(n) = ceiling(n/2)^3 + 3*(-1)^n for all n > 1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 10 2021

A052281.name: Number of 4 X 4 symmetric stochastic matrices under row and column permutations.

formula: G.f. for n-th row: Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n, k)*((1+x)^k-1)^(n-k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 04 2003

A052303.name: Number of asymmetric Greg trees.
formula: G.f.: 1+B(x)-B(x)^2 where B(x) is g.f. of A052301.

A052306.name: Product of exponents of prime factorization of n by prime signature: A005361(A025487).

A052307.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of bracelets (reversible necklaces) with n beads, k of which are black and n - k are white.
formula: T(0,0) = 1. If n > 0, T(n,k) = binomial(floor(n/2) - (k mod 2) * (1 - (n mod 2)), floor(k/2)) / 2 + Sum_{d|n, d|k} (phi(d)*binomial(n/d, k/d)) / (2*n). - _Washington Bomfim_, Jun 30 2012 [edited by _Petros Hadjicostas_, May 29 2019]
T(n,k) = T(n, n-k) for each k < n (Theorem 2 of H. Gupta). (End)
G.f. for column k >= 1: (x^k/2) * ((1/k) * Sum_{m|k} phi(m)/(1 - x^m)^(k/m) + (1 + x)/(1 - x^2)^floor((k/2) + 1)). (This formula is due to Herbert Kociemba.) - _Petros Hadjicostas_, May 25 2019

A052313.name: Triangle read by rows: matrix square of A047996.

A052316.name: Number of labeled rooted trees with n nodes and 2-colored internal (non-leaf) nodes.
formula: Divides by 2n and shifts left under exponential transform.
a(n) = sum(j=1..n, j^(n-1)*2^j*(-1)^(n-j)*binomial(n,j)), n>1, a(1)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jan 24 2012

A052317.name: Number of labeled trees with n nodes and 2-colored internal (non-leaf) nodes.
formula: E.g.f.: 1 + B(x) - x*B(x) - B(x)^2/2 where B(x) is g.f. of A052316.

A052318.name: Number of labeled rooted trimmed trees with n nodes.
formula: a(n) ~ sqrt(1 + LambertW(-2*exp(-2))) * 2^(n/2) * n^(n-1) / (exp(n) * (-LambertW(-2*exp(-2)))^(n/2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 08 2014

A052319.name: Number of increasing rooted trimmed trees with n nodes.
formula: E.g.f.: A(x) = 1/B(-x) where B'(x) is e.g.f. of A006882 and B(0) = 1.

A052320.name: Number of labeled trimmed trees with n nodes.

A052322.name: Number of labeled rooted trees with a forbidden limb of length 3.
formula: a(n) ~ sqrt(1+LambertW(-3*exp(-3))) * n^(n-1) * exp(n/3*LambertW(-3*exp(-3))). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 08 2014

A052323.name: Number of labeled trees with a forbidden limb of length 3.

A052326.name: Number of asymmetric trees with a forbidden limb of length 3.

formula: a(n) satisfies a = SHIFT_RIGHT(EULER(a-b)) where b(4)=1, b(k)=0 if k != 4.

A052328.name: Number of rooted trees with a forbidden limb of length 5.
formula: a(n) satisfies a = SHIFT_RIGHT(EULER(a-b)) where b(5)=1, b(k)=0 if k != 5.

A052329.name: Number of rooted trees with a forbidden limb of length 6.
formula: a(n) satisfies a=SHIFT_RIGHT(EULER(a-b)) where b(6)=1, b(k)=0 if k != 6.

A052330.name: Let S_k denote the first 2^k terms of this sequence and let b_k be the smallest positive integer that is not in S_k; then the numbers b_k*S_k are the next 2^k terms.
formula: a(0)=1; a(n+2^k)=a(n)*b(k) for n < 2^k, k = 0, 1, ... where b is A050376. - _Thomas Ordowski_, Mar 04 2005

A052331.name: Inverse of A052330; A binary encoding of Fermi-Dirac factorization of n, shown in decimal.
formula: a(1)=0; a(n*A050376(k)) = a(n) + 2^k for a(n) < 2^k, k=0, 1, ... - _Thomas Ordowski_, Mar 23 2005

A052332.name: Number of labeled digraphs where every node has indegree 0 or outdegree 0 and no isolated nodes.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n, k)*(2^k-2)^(n-k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 04 2003

a(n) = p(n,1,1) with p(n,t,k) = if t<0 then 0 else if k<=n then p(n-k,t-1,k)+p(n,k+1,k+1) else 0^n. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 20 2010

A052337.name: Number of partitions into at most a(1) copies of 1, a(2) copies of 2, ...

A052339.name: Values of n at which record values in A052340 are reached.

A052340.name: Record numbers of iterations reached in A050412.

A052341.name: Shifts left two places under BIN1 transform.

A052342.name: Shifts left under Stirling-Bernoulli transform.
formula: Stirling-Bernoulli transform sends a to b where b(n) = Sum_{i=0..n} (-1)^i*i!*S(n+1, i+1)*b(i).

A052343.name: Number of ways to write n as the unordered sum of two triangular numbers (zero allowed).
formula: G.f.: (Sum_{k>=0} x^(k^2 + k)) * (Sum_{k>=0} x^(k^2)). - _Michael Somos_, Aug 18 2003

Convolution of A005369 and A010052. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 28 2015

formula: G.f.: (Theta_2(sqrt(x))^2 - 4*x^(1/8)*Theta_2(sqrt(x)) + 2*Theta_2(x))/(8*x^(1/4)) where Theta_2 is a Jacobi theta function. - _Robert Israel_, Feb 24 2016
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} c(k) * c(2*n-k), where c(n) is the characteristic function of promic numbers (A005369). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 09 2021

A052355.name: First prime from A031930 (=lesser of 12-twins) with increasing distance to the next 12-twin.

A052356.name: First prime from A031932 whose distance to the next 14-twin increases.

formula: a(n) is the initial term of a [p, p+8, p+12, p+12+8] quadruple of consecutive primes.

formula: a(n) is the initial prime of a [p, p+4, p+6, p+6+4] prime-quadruple consisting of two 4-twins: [p, p+4] and [p+6, p+10].

A052379.name: Number of integers from 1 to 10^(n+1)-1 that lack 0 and 1 as a digit.
formula: a(n) = sum(k=1..n, 8^k). - corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Sep 25 2014

Conjecture: a(n) = A023001(n+2)-1. - _R. J. Mathar_, May 18 2007. Comment from _Vim Wenders_, Mar 26 2008: The conjecture is true: the g.f. leads to the closed form a(n) = -8/7*(1^n) + 64/7*(8^n) = (-8 + 64*8^n)/7 = (-8 + 8^(n+2))/7 = (8^(n+2) - 1)/7 -1 = A023001(n+2)-1.

A052380.name: a(n) = D is the smallest distance (D) between 2 non-overlapping prime twins differing by d=2n; these twins are [p,p+d] or [p+D,p+D+d] and p > 3.

A052381.name: The smallest initial prime of 2 non-overlapping d-twin primes if the distance between pairs (D) is minimal (see A052380).
formula: Smallest p so that [p, p+2n], [p+min{D}, p+2n+min{D}] is a quadruple (or triple if d=min{D}) of consecutive primes.

A052382.name: Numbers without 0 as a digit, a.k.a. zeroless numbers.
formula: a(n+1) = f(a(n)) with f(x) = 1 + if x mod 10 < 9 then x else 10*f([x/10]). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Nov 15 2009
From _Hieronymus Fischer_, Apr 30, May 30, Jun 08 2012, Feb 17 2019: (Start)
lim inf a(n)/10^log_9(8*n) = 1/10, for n -> infinity.
lim inf a(n)/n^(1/log_10(9)) = 8^(1/log_10(9))/10, for n -> infinity.
lim sup a(n)/10^log_9(8*n) = 1/9, for n -> infinity.
lim sup a(n)/n^(1/log_10(9)) = 8^(1/log_10(9))/9, for n -> infinity.
Generic formulas for analogous sequences with numbers expressed in base p and only using the digits 1, 2, 3, ... d, where 1 < d < p:
a(n) = Sum_{j=0..m-1} (1 + b(j) mod d)*p^j, where m = floor(log_d((d-1)*n+1)), b(j) = floor(((d-1)*n+1-d^m)/((d-1)*d^j)).
a(n) <= (10^log_d((d-1)*n+1)-1)/9, equality holds for n = (d^k-1)/(d-1), k > 0.
lim inf a(n)/10^log_d((d-1)*n) = d/90, for n -> infinity.
lim sup a(n)/10^log_d((d-1)*n) = 1/9, for n -> infinity.

G.f.: g(x) = (1/(1-x)) Sum_{j>=0} (1 - (d+1)(x^d^j)^d + d(x^d^j)^(d+1))*x^d^j*f_j(x)/(1-x^d^j), where f_j(x) = p^j*x^((d^j-1)/(d-1))/(1-(x^d^j)^d). Here, the f_j obey the recursion f_0(x) = 1/(1-x^d), f_(j+1)(x) = px*f_j(x^d).

Sum_{n>=1} 1/a(n) = 23.1034479... = A082839. This so-called Kempner series converges very slowly. For the calculation of the sum, it is helpful to use the following fraction of partial sums, which converges rapidly:

A052383.name: Numbers without 1 as a digit.
formula: a(1) = 1, a(n + 1) = f(a(n) + 1, a(n) + 1) where f(x, y) = if x < 10 and x <> 1 then y else if x mod 10 = 1 then f(y + 1, y + 1) else f(floor(x/10), y). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 02 2008
a(n) is the replacement of all nonzero digits d by d + 1 in the base-9 representation of n - 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Oct 07 2014

A052384.name: Number of letters in the n-th decimal digit of Pi (in English).

A052385.name: a(n)*10^n are the denominators of the greedy alternating Egyptian fraction expansion of Pi - 3 of the form Sum_{n>=0} ((-1)^n / (a(n)*10^n).

A052386.name: Number of integers from 1 to 10^n-1 that lack 0 as a digit.
formula: a(n) = 9*(9^n-1)/8 = sum_{j=1..n} 9^j = a(n-1)+9^n = 9*A002452(n) = A002452(n+1)-1; write A000918(n+1) in base 2 and read as if written in base 9. - _Henry Bottomley_, Aug 30 2001

A052388.name: Number of 4 X n binary matrices such that any 2 rows have a common 1, up to column permutations.

A052391.name: Number of 4-element intersecting families (of distinct sets) whose union is an n-element set.

A052392.name: T(2n+1,n), array T as in A054120.

A052393.name: Number of unlabeled ternary cacti having n triangles.
formula: a(n) = (1/n)*(Sum_{d|n} phi(n/d)*binomial(3*d, d)) - 2*binomial(3*n, n)/(2*n+1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, May 02 2018

A052394.name: Number of unlabeled 4-ary cacti having n polygons
formula: a(n) = (1/n)*(Sum_{d|n} phi(n/d)*binomial(4*d, d)) - 3*binomial(4*n, n)/(3*n+1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, May 02 2018

formula: a(n) = (1/n)*(Sum_{d|n} mu(n/d)*binomial(4*d, d)) - 3*binomial(4*n, n)/(3*n+1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Apr 30 2018

A052465.name: a(n) is the smallest positive integral solution k to 24*k == 1 (mod 11^n).
formula: a(n) = (1 + 23*11^n)/24, if n is even, and a(n) = (1 + 13*11^n)/24, if n is odd.
a(n) - a(n-1) = 10*11^(n-1), if n is even >= 2, and 5*11^(n-1), if n is odd >= 3. (End)

A052466.name: a(n) is the smallest positive solution k to 24*k == 1 (mod 13^n).
formula: a(n) = (1 + 11*13^n)/24, if n is odd, and a(n) = (1 + 23*13^n)/24, if n is even.
a(n) - a(n-1) = 12*13^(n-1) for n even >= 2, and 5*13^(n-1) for n odd >= 3. (End)

formula: Let z(n) = 2*(2*n+1)!*4^(-n-1)/((n+1)!)^2, then a(n) = numerator(z(n)), A162442(n) = denominator(z(n)), and z(n) = 1/(n+1) - Sum_{k=0..n}(-1)^k*binomial(n,k)*z(k). - _Groux Roland_, Jan 04 2011

A(x) satisfies A'(x)*( 1 - A(x)^2) = 1. _Robert Israel_ remarks that consequently A(x) is a root of z^3 - 3*z + 3*x with A(0) = 0. Cf. A001147, A052504 and A060706. - _Peter Bala_, Jan 02 2015

formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n, k)*(n-k-1)^k. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 12 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n, k)*k!*Stirling2(n-k, k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 19 2004
a(n) ~ exp((1-r*(n+r))/(1+r)) * n^(n+1/2) * sqrt(1+r) / (r^n * sqrt((1+r)^3 + n*(1+3*r+r^2))), where r satisfies exp(r)*(1+r) - (1+n)/r = 1. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Aug 04 2014

A052507.name: Take n-th palindromic prime p, let P = all primes having same digits; a(n) = q-p where q is smallest prime in P >p if q exists; otherwise a(n) = p-r where r is largest prime in P

A052508.name: Smallest number such that the largest set of positive real numbers whose sum and product equals the number falls short by n.

A052509.name: Knights-move Pascal triangle: T(n,k), n >= 0, 0 <= k <= n; T(n,0) = T(n,n) = 1, T(n,k) = T(n-1,k) + T(n-2,k-1) for k = 1,2,...,n-1, n >= 2.
formula: T(n, k) = Sum_{m=0..n} binomial(n-k, k-m). - _Wouter Meeussen_, Oct 03 2002
Referring to the square array T(i,j):
G.f. of row n: Sum_{k>=0} T(n,k) * x^k = (1+x)^n / (1-x).
Let a_i(n) be multiplicative with a_i(p^e) = T(i, e), p prime and e >= 0, then Sum_{n>0} a_i(n)/n^s = (zeta(s))^(i+1) / (zeta(2*s))^i for i >= 0.

A052510.name: Number of labeled planar binary trees with 2n-1 elements (external nodes or internal nodes).

A052512.name: Number of rooted labeled trees of height at most 2.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} n*C(n-1,k)*(n-k-1)^k. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Mar 15 2013

A052513.name: Number of labeled trees of height at most 3.

A052514.name: Number of labeled trees of height at most 4.

A052515.name: Number of ordered pairs of complementary subsets of an n-set with both subsets of cardinality at least 2.

A052516.name: Number of pairs of sets of cardinality at least 3.
formula: E.g.f.: (exp(x) - 1 - x - x^2/2)^2. - _Dennis P. Walsh_, Dec 09 2014

A052517.name: Number of ordered pairs of cycles over all n-permutations having two cycles.
formula: a(n) ~ 2*(n-1)!*log(n)*(1+gamma/log(n)), where gamma is Euler-Mascheroni constant (A001620). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 08 2012
0 = a(n) * n^2 - a(n+1) * (2*n+1) + a(n+2) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 23 2014
For n>=2, a(n) = (n-2)! * Sum_{i=1..n-1} Sum_{j=1..n-1} (i+j)/(i*j). - _Pedro Caceres_, Feb 14 2021

A052518.name: Number of pairs of cycles of cardinality at least 2.
formula: a(n) = 2*(n-2)!*((n-1)*(Psi(n) + gamma) - n), n>2. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 21 2003

A052519.name: Number of pairs of cycles of cardinality at least 3.

A052520.name: Number of pairs of sequences of cardinality at least 2.

A052521.name: Number of pairs of sequences of cardinality at least 3.

A052522.name: Number of labeled mobiles with cycles of length at least 3.
formula: E.g.f. A(x) is the series is reversion of 2*x-1/2*x^2-log(1+x). a(n) = (sum(k=0..n-1, (n+k-1)! * sum(j=0..k, 1/(k-j)! * sum(l=0..j, 1/l! * sum(i=0..l, ((-1)^(i+n+l-1) * 2^(l-2*i) * binomial(l,i) * stirling1(n+j-i-l-1,j-l))/(n+j-i-l-1)!))))), n > 0. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Feb 18 2012

A052523.name: Number of unlabeled mobiles with cycles of length at least 3.

A052524.name: Number of ordered labeled rooted trees on n nodes with non-leaf nodes having more than two children.
formula: E.g.f.: A(x)=sum_{n>0} a(n)*x^n/n! satisfies A(x)-A(x)^2-A(x)^3 = x*(1-A(x)).

a(n) ~ n^(n-1) * sqrt(r*(1-s)/(2+6*s)) / (exp(n) * r^n), where r = 0.2933671276754004454... is the root of the equation 5-8*r-32*r^2+4*r^3 = 0 and s = 0.40303171676268477587... is the root of the equation 1-2*s-2*s^2+2*s^3 = 0. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 08 2014

A052525.name: Number of unlabeled rooted trees with n leaves in which the degrees of the root and all internal nodes are >= 3.

A052526.name: Number of labeled rooted trees with n leaves in which the degrees of the root and all internal nodes are >= 3.

A052529.name: Expansion of (1-x)^3/(1 - 4*x + 3*x^2 - x^3).
formula: For n>0, a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} Sum_{i=0..k} Sum_{j=0..i} a(j). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jan 26 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n+2*k-1, n-k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 23 2003
If p[i]=i(i+1)/2 and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 02 2010
Recurrence equation: a(n) = Sum_{k = 1..n} 1/2*k*(k+1)*a(n-k) with a(0) = 1. - _Peter Bala_, Sep 19 2013

A052530.name: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - a(n-2), with a(0) = 0, a(1) = 2.
formula: Invert transform of even numbers: a(n) = 2*Sum_{k=1..n} k*a(n-k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 27 2001
a(n) = Sum(-(1/3)*(-1 + 2*alpha)*alpha^(-1 - n), alpha = root of (1 - 4*Z + Z^2),
a(n) = ((2 + sqrt(3))^n - (2 - sqrt(3))^n)/sqrt(3). (See Horadam for construction.) - _Johannes Boot_, Jan 08 2012
E.g.f.: (exp((2 + sqrt(3))*x) - exp((2 - sqrt(3))*x))/sqrt(3). - _Franck Maminirina Ramaharo_, Nov 12 2018

A052531.name: If n is even then 2^n+1 otherwise 2^n.

A052533.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-x-3*x^2).
formula: If p[1]=0, and p[i]=3, (i>1), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 29 2010
G.f.: (Q(0) -1)*(1-x)/x, where Q(k) = 1 + 3*x^2 + (k+2)*x - x*(k+1 + 3*x)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 07 2013

A052534.name: Expansion of (1-x)*(1+x)/(1-2*x-x^2+x^3).
formula: a(n) = central term in the (n+1)-th power of the 3 X 3 matrix (shown in the example of A066170): [1 1 1 / 1 1 0 / 1 0 0]. E.g. a(6) = 101 since the central term in M^7 = 101. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Feb 01 2004

a(n) = A077998(n+2) - 2*A006054(n+2), which implies 7*a(n-2) = (2 + c(4) - 2*c(2))*(1 + c(1))^n + (2 + c(1) - 2*c(4))*(1 + c(2))^n + (2 + c(2) - 2*c(1))*(1 + c(4))^n, where c(j)=2*Cos(2Pi*j/7), a(-2)=a(-1)=1 since A077998 and A006054 are equal to the respective quasi-Fibonacci numbers. [Witula, Slota and Warzynski] - _Roman Witula_, Aug 07 2012

A052535.name: Expansion of (1-x)*(1+x)/(1-x-2*x^2+x^4).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(2*n-3*k, k). - _Paul Barry_, Jan 21 2005

A052536.name: Number of compositions of n when parts 1 and 2 are of two kinds.
formula: a(n) = left term in M^n * [1 0 0], where M = the 3 X 3 matrix [2 1 1 / 1 1 0 / 1 0 0]. Right term in M^n *[1 0 0] is a(n-1); middle term is A076264(n-1). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Sep 05 2005

A052537.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-x-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..floor((n-1)/2)} binomial(n-1-2*k, k-1)*2^k, n>=1. - _Taras Goy_, Sep 18 2019

A052539.name: a(n) = 4^n + 1.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(x) + exp(4*x). - _Mohammad K. Azarian_, Jan 02 2009

A052540.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-x^3+x^4).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} ( Sum_{j=ceiling((-n+3*k+1)/3)..k} binomial(k,j)* binomial(n-3*(k-j)-1,j-1) ) + kron_delta(3*k,n)). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 12 2013

A052541.name: Expansion of 1/(1-3*x-x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/3)} binomial(n-2*k, k) * 3^(n-3*k). - _Paul Barry_, Oct 20 2004

A052542.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-2), with a(0) = 1, a(1) = 2, a(2) = 4.
formula: a(n) = 2*A001333(n-1) + a(n-1), n > 1. A001333(n)/a(n) converges to sqrt(1/2). - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), Apr 29 2003
Binomial transform of A094024. a(n) = 0^n + ((1 + sqrt(2))^n - (1 - sqrt(2))^n)/sqrt(2). - _Paul Barry_, Apr 22 2004
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-k-1, k)2^(n-2k). - _Paul Barry_, Jan 16 2005

If p[i] = 2modp(i,2) and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by A[i,j] = p[j-i+1], (i <= j), A[i,j] = -1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j] = 0 otherwise. Then, for n >= 1, a(n) = det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 02 2010
G.f.: 1 + x + x^2/(2*G(0)-x) where G(k) = 1 - (k+1)/(1 - x/(x +(k+1)/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 07 2012
G.f.: G(0)*(1-x)/(2*x) + 1 - 1/x, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k-1)/(x*(2*k+1) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 26 2013
G.f.: 1 + G(0)*x/(1-x), where G(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k-1)/(x*(2*k+1) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 19 2013
G.f.: 1 + (1+G(0))/(2-2*x), where G(k) = 2*x*(k+2) - 1 - x + x*(2*k-1)/G(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 14 2013
G.f.: Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 + (1+x)*x + (2*k+3)*x - x*(2*k+1 + x+1)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 04 2013
a(n) = round(sqrt(Pell(2n) + Pell(2n-1))). - _Richard R. Forberg_, Jun 22 2014

A052543.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1 - 3*x - 2*x^2 + 2*x^3).
formula: Equals triangle A059260 * the Pell sequence [1, 2, 5, 12, ...] as a vector. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Mar 06 2012

A052544.name: Expansion of (1-x)^2/(1 - 4*x + 3*x^2 - x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n+2*k, 3*k). - _Richard L. Ollerton_, May 12 2004
G.f.: 1 / (1 - x - x / (1 - x)^2). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 12 2012

A052548.name: a(n) = 2^n + 2.
formula: a(n) = A058896(n)/A000918(n), for n>0. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 14 2009
a(n) = A173786(n,1), for n>0. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 28 2010
a(n)*A000918(n) = A028399(2*n), for n>0. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 28 2010

A052549.name: a(n) = 5*2^(n-1) - 1, n>0, with a(0)=1.
formula: Equals row sums of triangle A133601. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Sep 18 2007

A052550.name: Expansion of (1-2*x)/(1 - 3*x - x^2 + 2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum((-1/229) * (-5 - 74*alpha + 16*alpha^2) * alpha^(-1-n), alpha = RootOf(1 - 3*z - z^2 + 2*z^3)).

A052551.name: Expansion of 1/((1 - x)*(1 - 2*x^2)).
formula: a(n) = -1 + Sum((1/2)*(1 + 2*alpha)*alpha^(-1 - n)) where the sum is over alpha = the two roots of -1 + 2*x^2.
a(n-2) = S2(floor(n/2)+1,2), where S2 is the Stirling subset number A008277.
E.g.f.: 2*cosh(sqrt(2)*x) + sqrt(2)*sinh(sqrt(2)*x) - cosh(x) - sinh(x). - _Franck Maminirina Ramaharo_, Nov 23 2018

A052553.name: Square array of binomial coefficients T(n,k) = binomial(n,k), n >= 0, k >= 0, read by antidiagonals.
formula: G.f. of the triangular version: 1/(1-x-x^2*y). - _R. J. Mathar_, Aug 11 2015

A052554.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: (1-x)/(1 - x - x^2).
formula: a(n) = n!*Fibonacci(n-1) for n >= 1. - Bob Proctor, Apr 19 2005
a(0) = 1; a(n) = Sum_{k=2..n} binomial(n,k) * k! * a(n-k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Feb 09 2020

A052558.name: a(n) = n! *((-1)^n + 2*n + 3)/4.
formula: Let u(1)=1, u(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} u(k)*k*(-1)^(k-1) then a(n) = abs(u(n+2)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Nov 14 2003
a(n) = (n+1)!/2 if n is odd; a(n) = n!(n+2)/2 if n is even. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Jul 18 2009
E.g.f.: G(0)/(1+x) where G(k) = 1 + 2*x*(k+1)/((2*k+1) - x*(2*k+1)*(2*k+3)/(x*(2*k+3) + 2*(k+1)/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 21 2012

A052560.name: a(n) = 3*n!.
formula: For n>0: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n+1} A083746(k). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 14 2007

A052562.name: a(n) = 5^n * n!.
formula: G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 - 5*x*(2*k+1) - 25*x^2*(k+1)^2/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 28 2013

A052564.name: Expansion of e.g.f. x*(1-x)/(1-2*x).
formula: a(n) = A002866(n) - A014297(n-2) for n>1. - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Mar 05 2010

A052566.name: E.g.f.: (2 + x)/(1 - x^2).
formula: a(n) = 2n! if n is even, n! if odd.

A052572.name: E.g.f. (1+2x-2x^2)/(1-x)^2.
formula: For n <= 1, a(n) = (n+1)^2, for n > 1, a(n) = (n+1)! + 2*n! - _Antti Karttunen_, Sep 24 2016

A052582.name: a(n) = 2*n*n!.
formula: Sum_{n>=1} 1/a(n) = (Ei(1) - gamma)/2 = (A091725 - A001620)/2, where Ei(x) is the exponential integral.

A052584.name: E.g.f. (2-4x+x^2)/((1-x)(1-2x)).
formula: A weighted binomial sum of the Bernoulli numbers A027641/A027642 with A027641(1)=1 (which amounts to the definition B_{n} = B_{n}(1)).

A052585.name: E.g.f. 1/(1-x-2*x^2).
formula: a(n) = D^n(1/(1-x)) evaluated at x = 0, where D is the operator sqrt(1+8*x)*d/dx. Cf. A080599 and A005442. - Peter Bala, Dec 07 2011

A052589.name: a(n) = (2^n - 1)*n!.
formula: G.f.: -G(0) where G(k) = 1 - 2^k/(1 - x*(k+1)/(x*(k+1) - 2^k/G(k+1) )), (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 06 2012
If A(x) = Sum_{k>0} x^k / a(k), then A(2*x) = A(x) + e^x - 1.

A052591.name: E.g.f. x/((1-x)(1-x^2)).
formula: a(n) = (n+1)!/2 if n is odd; a(n) = n!n/2 if n is even. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Jul 18 2009

A052600.name: E.g.f. 1/((1-2*x)*(1-x^2)).
formula: a(n) = (4*2^n-1)/3*n! if n is even, a(n) = (4*2^n-2)/3*n! otherwise.

A052612.name: E.g.f. x*(2+x)/(1-x^2).
formula: n! if n is even, 2n! otherwise. a(n) = n!*A000034(n).
a(n) = n! / gcd(n, T(n)) where T(n) is the n-th triangular number. - _Andrew S. Plewe_, Jan 09 2006

A052619.name: E.g.f. 3x^3/(1-x).
formula: E.g.f. G(0)*3*x^3 where G(k)= 1 + x/(1 - x/( x + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction, 3rd kind, 3-step). - Sergei N. Gladkovskii, Jul 28 2012

A052621.name: E.g.f. (2+x+x^2+x^3)/(1-x^4).
formula: 2n! if n is 0 mod 4, n! otherwise.

A052633.name: E.g.f. x^2*(1+x-x^2)/(1-x)^2.
formula: Recurrence: {a(0)=0, a(1)=0, a(2)=2, a(3)=18; for n > 3, a(n) = a(n-1)*n^2/(n-1)}. [Simplified by _Jon E. Schoenfield_, Aug 11 2017]

A052636.name: E.g.f. (2-x-2x^2)/((1-x)(1-2x^2)).
formula: n!*[2^(n/2)+1] if n is even, n! otherwise.

A052644.name: E.g.f. (1+3x-3x^2)/(1-x)^2.
formula: G.f.: G(0)  where G(k) = 1 + x*(k+1)*(k+4)/(1 - 1/(1 + (k+4)/G(k+1)) ; (continued fraction, 3-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 16 2012

A052649.name: E.g.f. (2+x-x^2)/(1-x)^2.
formula: a(0) = 2; for n >= 1, a(n) = 2*(n+1)! + n! - _Antti Karttunen_, Sep 24 2016

A052673.name: a(n) = 3*n*n!.
formula: a(n) = A122972(n+2) - A122972(n) for n > 0. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Sep 21 2006
For n>0: a(n) = A083746(n+2). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 14 2007

A052676.name: E.g.f. 3*x/(1 - 2*x).
formula: Recurrence: a(0) = 0, a(1) = 3, and (-2*n - 2)*a(n) + a(n+1) = 0 for n >= 1.

A052701.name: a(0) = 0; for n >= 1, a(n) = 2^(n-1)*C(n-1), where C(n) = A000108(n) Catalan numbers, n>0.
formula: G.f.: (1-sqrt(1-8*x))/4 = x*C(2*x) where C(x) is g.f. for Catalan numbers, A000108.
G.f. A(x) satisfies 2*A(x)^2-A(x)+x=0, A(0)=0 and A(x)=x+2*A(x)^2=x/(1-2*A(x)). Series reversion of x-2*x^2. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 06 2003
a(0)=0, a(1)=1; a(n) = 2*Sum_{i=1..n-1} a(i)*a(n-i). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 16 2004
With a different offset, a(0)=1, a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{j=0..n} (j*C(2n-j-1, n-j)*C(j, k)*2^(n-j)/n), n>0. - _Paul Barry_, Jul 24 2005
The Hankel transform of a(n+1) = [1,2,8,40,224,1344,...] is 4^C(n+1,2). - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 06 2007
G.f.: x + 4*x^2/(G(0)-4*x) where G(k) = k*(8*x+1) + 4*x + 2 - 2*x*(2*k+3)*(2*k+4)/G(k+1) ; (continued fraction ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 05 2013

A052704.name: Apart from the leading term, a(n) = Catalan(n-1)*4^(n-1).
formula: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(n) = 4*Sum_{i=1..n-1} a(i)*a(n-i). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 16 2004
a(n+1) = (1/(8*Pi))*Integral_{x=0..16} x^n*sqrt(x*(16-x))/x dx; a(n+1) = (1/(8*Pi))*Integral_{x=-4..4} x^(2*n)*sqrt(4-x)*sqrt(4+x)*dt. - _Paul Barry_, Oct 01 2007
a(n) = upper left term of M^(n-1), where M is an infinite matrix as follows:
a(n) = 4 * Sum_{k=1..n-1} a(k) * a(n-k) if n>1. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 23 2011

A052705.name: Expansion of 2*x^2/(1 - 2*x - 2*x^2 + sqrt(1 - 4*x - 4*x^2)).
formula: a(n+2) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{j=0..n} C(j,n-j)*A001263(j,k). - _Paul Barry_, Jun 30 2009
G.f.: A(x) satisfies A(x) = C(x*(1+A(x)))^2, where x*C(x) is g.f. of Catalan numbers. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jan 16 2015

A052707.name: Odd powers of 2 multiplied by Catalan numbers.
formula: Given g.f. A(x), then B(x)=A(x)-x series reversion is -B(-x). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 08 2005
Given g.f. A(x), then B(x)=A(x)-x satisfies B(x)=x+8*C(16*x*B(x)) where C(x) is g.f. for Catalan number A000108.
G.f. A(x) = 2*x*C(4*x) where C(x) is g.f. for Catalan number A000108.

A052709.name: Expansion of (1-sqrt(1-4x-4x^2))/(2(1+x)).
formula: G.f.: A(x) = x/(1-(1+x)*A(x)). [_Paul D. Hanna_, Aug 16 2002]
G.f.: A(x) = x/(1-z/(1-z/(1-z/(...)))) where z=x+x^2 (continued fraction). [_Paul D. Hanna_, Aug 16 2002; revised by _Joerg Arndt_, Mar 18 2011].
a(n+1) = sum{k=0..n, C(k)*C(k, n-k)} - _Paul Barry_, Feb 22 2005
G.f. is x*c(x*(1+x)) where c(x) is the g.f. of A000108. Row sums of A117434. - _Paul Barry_, Mar 14 2006
a(n), n>0 = upper left term in M^(n-1), where M = an infinite square production matrix as follows:
G.f.: x*Q(0), where Q(k)= 1 + (4*k+1)*x*(1+x)/(k+1 - x*(1+x)*(2*k+2)*(4*k+3)/(2*x*(1+x)*(4*k+3) + (2*k+3)/Q(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 14 2013

A052714.name: a(n) = 2^(n-1) * n! * Catalan(n-1) for n > 0 with a(0) = 0.
formula: a(n+1) = A090802(2n, n). - _Ross La Haye_, Oct 18 2005
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies differential equation A'(x)=1/(1-4*A(x)). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 04 2011
G.f.: 2*x/G(0), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - 2*x*(8*k+4)/(2*x*(8*k+4) - 1 + 16*x*(k+1)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 30 2013
a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1; a(n) = 2 * Sum_{k=1..n-1} binomial(n,k) * a(k) * a(n-k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 09 2020

A052760.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: x^2*(exp(x)-1)^2.

a(n) = n*A052749(n-1) = 2*n*(n-1)*Stirling2(n-2,2) for n >= 2. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Aug 08 2020

a(n) = n*A052761(n-1) =  3!*n*(n-1)*Stirling2(n-2,3) for n >= 2. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Aug 08 2020

A052782.name: a(n) = (5*n+1)^(n-1).

A052833.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: (log(2-exp(x)))^2.

formula: O.g.f.: Sum_{n>=0} (2*n)! * x^(2*n) / Product_{k=1..2*n} (1-k*x). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 20 2011
a(n) = D^n*(1/(1-x^2)) evaluated at x = 0, where D is the operator (1+x)*d/dx. Cf. A000670 and A005649. - _Peter Bala_, Nov 25 2011
E.g.f.: 1/2/G(0) where G(k) = 1 - 2^k/(2 - 4*x/(2*x - 2^k*(k+1)/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 22 2012
a(n) = (h(n)+(-1)^n)/2 where h(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} E(n,k)*2^k and E(n,k) the Eulerian numbers A173018 (see also A156365). - _Peter Luschny_, Sep 19 2015
a(n) = (-1)^n + Sum_{k=0..n-1} binomial(n,k) * a(k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 11 2020

a(0) = 1; a(n) = Sum_{k=2..n} binomial(n-1,k-1) * k! * a(n-k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Feb 09 2020

A052848.name: Number of ordered set partitions with a designated element in each block and no block containing less than two elements.

A052849.name: a(0) = 0; a(n+1) = 2*n! (n >= 0).

a(n) = A090802(n, n - 1) for n > 0. - _Ross La Haye_, Sep 26 2005
For n >= 1, a(n) = (n+3)!*Sum_((-1)^k*binomial(2, k)/(n + 3 - k), k = 0..n + 2). - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 14 2008
G.f.: 2/Q(0) - 2, where Q(k) = 1 - x*(k + 1)/(1 - x*(k + 1)/Q(k+1) ); (continued fraction ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 01 2013
G.f.: -2 + 2/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 + k*x - x*(k+1)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 01 2013
G.f.: W(0) - 2 , where W(k) = 1 + 1/( 1 - x*(k+1)/( x*(k+1) + 1/W(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 21 2013

A052852.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: (x/(1-x))*exp(x/(1-x)).

a(n) = D^n(x*exp(x)) evaluated at x = 0, where D is the operator (1+x)^2*d/dx. Cf. A000262 and A005493. - _Peter Bala_, Nov 25 2011
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} L(n,k)*k; L(n,k) the unsigned Lah numbers. - _Peter Luschny_, Oct 18 2014

The series reversion of the e.g.f. equals W(x)/(1 + W(x)) = x - 2^2*x^2/2! + 3^3*x^3/3! - 4^4*x^4/4! + ..., essentially the e.g.f. for a signed version of A000312, where W(x) is Lambert's W-function (see A000169). - _Peter Bala_, Jun 14 2016
Equals column A059114(n, 2) for n >= 1. - _G. C. Greubel_, Feb 23 2021

A052853.name: A simple grammar.
formula: G.f. appears to be -Sum_{j>=1} (phi(j)/j) * log(1-C(x^j)), where phi = A000010 and C is the g.f. of A050383. - _Robert Israel_, Nov 01 2016

A052854.name: Number of forests of ordered trees on n total nodes.
formula: Euler transform of Catalan numbers C(n-1) (cf. A000108).
n*a(n)=Sum_{k=1..n} a(n-k)*b(k), b(k)=Sum_{d|k} binomial(2*d-2, d-1)=A066768(k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jan 17 2002
G.f.: 1/(Product_{k>0} (1-x^k)^C(k-1)) where C() is Catalan numbers.
G.f.: A(z) = prod_{n >= 1} (1-z^n)^(-A000108(n)) = exp(sum_{k >= 1} C(z^k)/k, where C(z) is the g.f. for the Catalan numbers.

A052855.name: Number of forests of rooted trees of nonempty sets with n points. (Each node is a set of 1 or more points.)
formula: G.f. satisfies: A(x) = exp( Sum_{n>=1} A(x^n)/(1-x^n) * x^n/n  ). [From Paul D. Hanna, Oct 26 2011]

A052857.name: A simple grammar.
formula: a(n) = n!*hypergeom([-n+2], [2], -n) for n>=2. - _Peter Luschny_, Apr 20 2016
a(n) ~ exp(n/phi - n) * phi^(2*n-2) * n^(n-1) / 5^(1/4), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 01 2017
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x*exp(A(x)/(1 - A(x))). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 04 2019
a(n) = n * (n-2)! * LaguerreL(n-2, 1, -n) with a(0) = 0 and a(1) = 1. - _G. C. Greubel_, Feb 23 2021

A052858.name: E.g.f.: log(-1/(-1+x*exp(x)-x)).
formula: a(n) ~ (n-1)! * r^n, where r = 1.23997788765655... is the root of the equation log(1+r)=1/r. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 29 2013

A052859.name: A simple grammar.
formula: Stirling transform of unsigned Hermite numbers: Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling2(n, k)*|HermiteH(k, 0)|. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 12 2003

A052860.name: A simple grammar: rooted sequences of cycles.
formula: a(n) = n*A007840(n-1). a(n) = n!*Sum_{k=0..n-1} a(k)/k!/(n-k) for n>=1 with a(0)=0. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 19 2006

A052866.name: Expansion of e.g.f. x/(1 - x) + exp(x/(1 - x)).
formula: a(n) = n! + A000262(n) for n>0. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 29 2002

A052868.name: E.g.f.: LambertW(x/(-1+x))/x*(-1+x).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} n!/k!*binomial(n-1, k-1)*(k+1)^(k-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 17 2003
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies  A(x) = exp( x*A(x)/(1-x) ) - _Olivier Gérard_, Dec 28 2013

A052872.name: A simple grammar.
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies [from _Paul D. Hanna_, Oct 16 2013]:
(2) A(x) = exp( Sum_{n>=1} x^n/n * Sum_{d|n} d*A(x^(n/d))^d ).

A052873.name: E.g.f. satisfies: A(x) = exp(x*A(x)/(1 - x*A(x))).
formula: E.g.f. satisfies: A(x) = Sum_{n>=0} (n+1)^(n-1)*x^n/n! / (1-x*A(x))^n. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Sep 08 2012
E.g.f. satisfies: A(x) = exp( x*A(x)/(1 - x*A(x)) ). - _Olivier Gérard_, Dec 29 2013
a(n) = n!*hypergeom([1-n],[2],-n-1) for n>=1. - _Peter Luschny_, Apr 20 2016

A052875.name: E.g.f.: (exp(x)-1)^2/(2-exp(x)).
formula: Second column of A084416: Sum_{i=2..n} i!*Stirling2(n, i) = A000670(n)-1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 15 2003
E.g.f.: A(x)*(1/(1 - A(x)) - 1) where A(x)=exp(x)-1. - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Sep 01 2014

A052878.name: E.g.f.: log((1-x)/(1-3*x+x^2)).
formula: For n > 0, a(n) = (n-1)! * (phi^(2*n) + 1/phi^(2*n) - 1), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jun 06 2019

A052879.name: Number of objects generated by the Combstruct grammar defined in the Maple program. See the link for the grammer specification.
formula: G.f.: g(x)/(x*(1 + g(x))) where g(x) is the g.f. of A052836. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Aug 09 2020

A052880.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: -LambertW(-exp(x)+1)/(exp(x)-1).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling2(n, k)*(k+1)^(k-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 12 2003
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = Sum_{n>=0} x^n/n! * Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling2(n,k) * A(x)^k. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 09 2013
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = exp((exp(x) - 1)*A(x)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 04 2019

A052881.name: E.g.f.: log(1/(1-x))*x/(1-x).
formula: a(n) ~ n!*log(n)*(1+gamma/log(n)), where gamma is Euler-Mascheroni constant (A001620). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 09 2012

A052882.name: A simple grammar: rooted ordered set partitions.
formula: a(n) = (1/2)*sum(k=0, n-1, B_k*A000629(k)*binomial(n, k)) where B_k is the k-th Bernoulli number. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 19 2005
a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1; a(n) = n! * [x^n] exp(x)*Sum_{k=1..n-1} a(k)*x^k/k!. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 17 2017

A052883.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: log((-1+x)/(-1+2*x))^2.
formula: a(n) ~ (n-1)! * 2^(n+1)* (log(n) + gamma - log(2)), where gamma is Euler-Mascheroni constant (A001620). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 29 2013

A052884.name: Number of objects generated by the Combstruct grammar defined in the Maple program. See the link for the grammar specification.
formula: G.f.: 1/(1 - x*g(x)) - 1 where g(x) is the g.f. of A052872. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Aug 09 2020

A052885.name: E.g.f. A(x) is inverse to F(x) = x*exp(-x)/(1+x).
formula: E.g.f. A(x) = sum(n>0, a(n)*x^n/n!) is inverse to F(x)=x*exp(-x)/(1+x), a(n)=(n-1)!*sum_{i=0..n-1} (n^(n-i-1)*binomial(n,i))/(n-i-1)!, n>0. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jan 31 2012

A052886.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: (1/2) - (1/2)*(5 - 4*exp(x))^(1/2).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} k!*Stirling2(n,k)*C(k-1), where C(k) = Catalan numbers (A000108). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Sep 15 2010
Equals the logarithmic derivative of A293379. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Oct 22 2017
O.g.f.: Sum_{k>=1} C(k-1)*Product_{r=1..k} r*x/(1-r*x), where C = A000108. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Jun 12 2020

A052887.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: exp(x^2/(1 - x)^2).
formula: a(n) = n!*y(n) with y(0) = 1 and y(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} (n-k)*(n-k-1)*y(k)/n for n >= 1. - _Benedict W. J. Irwin_, Jun 02 2016

A052888.name: E.g.f. is series reversion of log(1+x)*exp(-x).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} Stirling2(n, k)*n^(k-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jul 26 2005
a(n) = exp(-n)*Sum_{k>=1} n^(k-1)*k^n/k!. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jul 03 2006 [corrected by _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 20 2020]
a(n) ~ exp(n*(LambertW(1) + 1/LambertW(1) - 2)) * n^(n-1) / sqrt(1+LambertW(1)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 22 2014

A052889.name: Number of rooted set partitions.
formula: Let A be the upper Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,i-1]=-1, A[i,j]=binomial(j-1,i-1), (i<=j), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n)=(-1)^(n-1)*coeff(charpoly(A,x),x). - _Milan Janjic_, Jul 08 2010

A052891.name: Number of objects generated by the Combstruct grammar defined in the Maple program. See the link for the grammar specification.
formula: G.f.: 1 - 1/g(x) where g(x) is the g.f. of A052893. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Aug 09 2020

A052892.name: E.g.f. is series reversion of log(1+x)*(1-x).
formula: a(n) = sum(i=0..n-1, binomial(n-1,i)*sum(k=0..i, stirling2(i,k)*k!* binomial(n+k-1,k))). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jan 22 2014
a(n) ~ n^(n-1) * (c/2)^(n-1) / (sqrt(c+1) * exp(n) * (c-1)^(2*n-1)), where c = LambertW(2*exp(1)) = 1.3748225281836... - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 22 2014

A052893.name: Number of objects generated by the Combstruct grammar defined in the Maple program. See the link for the grammar specification.
formula: G.f.: 1/(1 - g(x)) where g(x) is the g.f. of A052891. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Aug 09 2020

A052894.name: a(n) is the number of Schröder trees on n vertices with a prescribed root.
formula: (4) A(x) = Sum_[n>=0} exp(n*x*A(x)) / 2^(n+1). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Apr 07 2018

A052895.name: E.g.f.: (1/2)/(exp(x) - 1) * (1 - (5 - 4*exp(x))^(1/2)).
formula: E.g.f.: 1/(1 + (1 - exp(x))/(1 + (1 - exp(x))/(1 + (1 - exp(x))/(1 + (1 - exp(x))/(1 + ...))))), a continued fraction. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 18 2017
E.g.f.: C(exp(x) - 1), where C(x) = (1 - sqrt(1 - 4*x))/(2*x) is the o.g.f. for A000108. Cf. A006531.

Conjecture: for fixed k = 1,2,..., the sequence a(n) (mod k) is eventually periodic with the exact period dividing phi(k), where phi(k) is the Euler totient function A000010. For example, modulo 10 the sequence becomes (1, 1, 5, 3, 5, 1, 5, 3, 5, ...), with an apparent period 1, 5, 3, 5 of length 4 = phi(10) beginning at a(1). (End)
O.g.f.: 1 + Sum_{k>=1} A000108(k)*Product_{r=1..k} r*x/(1 - r*x). - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Jun 12 2020

A052896.name: E.g.f.: (exp(exp(x)-1)-1)^2.
formula: For n >= 1: a(n) = Sum_{k=0...n} Stirling2(n,k)*(2^k-2) where Stirling2(n,k) is the number of set partitions of {1,2,...,n} into exactly k blocks (A008277).

A052897.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: exp(2*x/(1-x)).
formula: LAH transform of A000079: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n) 2^k*n!/k!*binomial(n-1, k-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Oct 17 2003

a(n) = n!*L(n,-1,-2). - _Karol A. Penson_, Oct 16 2006 [Here L(n,a,x) is the n-th generalized Laguerre polynomial with parameter a, evaluated at x. L(n,a,x) is 1 if n=0, a+1-x if n=1 and otherwise (2*n+a-1-x)/n*L(n-1,a,x)-(n+a-1)/n*L(n-2,a,x). - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 20 2011]
E.g.f.: 1 + 2*x/((1-x)*T(0) - x), where T(k) = 4*k+1 + x^2/((4*k+3)*(1-x)^2 + x^2/T(k+1) ); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 30 2013
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)*l(k)*l(n-k), where l(m) = A000262(m). - _Emanuele Munarini_, Aug 31 2017

A052898.name: 2*n! + 1.
formula: Let E(x) be the e.g.f., then
E(x)=(x*G(0)-2)/(x-1), where G(k)= 1 - 1/(x - x^3/(x^2 - (k+1)/G(k+1)));(continued fraction, 3rd kind, 3-step).

A052899.name: Expansion of g.f.: ( 1-2*x ) / ((x-1)*(4*x^2+2*x-1)).
formula: a(n)/a(n-1) tends to (1 + sqrt(5)) = 3.236067... - _Gary W. Adamson_, Mar 01 2008
a(n) = (1/5) * Sum_{k=1..5} ((x_k)^4-3*(x_k)^2+1), x_k=2*cos((2*k-1)*Pi/10). Also, a(n)/a(n-1) -> spectral radius of matrix A_(10,4) above. - _L. Edson Jeffery_, Apr 19 2011

A052902.name: Take n-th prime p, let P = all primes that can be obtained by permuting the digits of p and possibly omitting zeros; a(n) = |p-q| where q in P is the closest to p but different from p (a(n)=0 if no such q exists).

A052905.name: a(n) = (n^2 + 7*n + 2)/2.
formula: a(n) = n+a(n-1)+3, with n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 06 2010

A052906.name: Expansion of (1-x^2)/(1-3*x-x^2).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-k-1, k)*3^(n-2*k). - _Paul Barry_, Jan 16 2005

If p(i)=3*(i mod 2) and if A is the Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p(j-i+1), (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise, then, for n>=1, a(n)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 02 2010
G.f.: G(0)*(1-x^2)/(2-3*x), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - (x*(13*k-9))/( x*(13*k+4) - 6/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 15 2013
a(n) = 3*( ((3+sqrt(13))/2)^n - ((3-sqrt(13))/2)^n )/sqrt(13), for n>=1. - _Bogart B. Strauss_, Jul 19 2013
a(n) = 3*Fibonacci(n, 3) for n > 0, where Fibonacci(n, x) are the Fibonacci polynomials. - _G. C. Greubel_, Oct 14 2019

A052907.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - 2*x^2 - 2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(k, n-2*k)*2^k. - _Paul Barry_, Oct 19 2004

Construct the matrix T with elements T(n,j) = [A^*j]*[S^*(j-1)](n) with the sequences A = (0,2,2,0,0...) and S = (0,1,0,0...) and the convolution operation *. Define S^*0 = I = (1, repeat(0)). Then T(n,j) for j>=1, counts closed n-walks containing j loops on the graph defined above in a comment, and a(n) = Sum_{j=1..n} T(n,j). - _David Neil McGrath_, Jan 16 2015

A052911.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1 - 3*x - x^2 + 2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = center term in M^n * [1 1 1] where M = Hosoya's triangle considered as an upper triangular 3 X 3 matrix: [2 1 2 / 1 1 0 / 1 0 0]. E.g., a(4) = 66 since M^4 * [1 1 1] = [139 66 45]. The analogous procedure using M^n * [1 0 0] generates A100058. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 31 2004

A052912.name: Expansion of 1/(1-2*x-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(k, floor((n-k)/2)) * 2^k * (1+(-1)^(n-k))/2. - _Paul Barry_, Jan 12 2006
G.f.: Q(0)/2, where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(4*k+2 + 2*x^2)/( x*(4*k+4 + 2*x^2) + 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 30 2013

A052918.name: a(0) = 1, a(1) = 5, a(n+1) = 5*a(n) + a(n-1).
formula: a(n) = U(n, 5*i/2)*(-i)^n with i^2 = -1 and Chebyshev's U(n, x/2) = S(n, x) polynomials. See triangle A049310.
Let M = {{0, 1}, {1, 5}}, then a(n) is the lower-right term of M^n. - _Roger L. Bagula_, May 29 2005
a(n) = F(n, 5), the n-th Fibonacci polynomial evaluated at x = 5. - _T. D. Noe_, Jan 19 2006

a(n) = denominator of n-th convergent to [1, 4, 5, 5, 5,...], for n > 0. Continued fraction [1, 4, 5, 5, 5,...] = .807417596..., the inradius of a right triangle with legs 2 and 5. n-th convergent = A100237(n)/A052918(n), the first few being: 1/1, 4/5, 21/26, 109/135, 566/701,... - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 21 2007
Define the 2 X 2 matrix A = {{1, 1}, {5, 4}}. Then:
a(n) is the upper-left term of (1/5)*(A^(n+2) - A^(n+1));
a(n) is the upper-right term of A^(n+1);
a(n) is the lower-left term of (1/5)*A^(n+1);
a(n) is the lower-right term of (Sum_{k=0..n} A^k). (End)

A052919.name: a(n) = 1 + 2*3^(n-1) with a(0)=2.
formula: a(0) = 2 and a(n) = A100702(n) for n >= 1. - _Omar E. Pol_, Mar 02 2012

A052920.name: a(n) = a(n-3) + a(n-5) with initial values 1,0,0,1,0.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..j} ( (m'-2*i)!/(k'+3*i)!*(m'-k'-5*i)!) (see comments for definitions of variables).

A052921.name: Expansion of (1 - x)/(1 - 3*x + 2*x^2 - x^3).
formula: Binomial transform of the Padovan sequence A000931(n+5).

A052923.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1 - x - 4*x^2).
formula: If p[1]=0, and p[i]=4, ( i>1), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 29 2010

A052924.name: Expansion of g.f.: (1-x)/(1 - 3*x - x^2).
formula: With offset 1: a(1)=1; for n > 1, a(n) = Sum_{i=1..3n-4} a(ceiling(i/3))). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jan 04 2004
Binomial transform of A006130. a(n) = (1/2 - sqrt(13)/26)*(3/2 - sqrt(13)/2)^n + (1/2 + sqrt(13)/26)*(3/2 + sqrt(13)/2)^n. - _Paul Barry_, Jul 20 2004
Numerators in continued fraction [1, 2, 3, 3, 3, ...], where the latter = 0.69722436226...; the length of an inradius of a right triangle with legs 2 and 3. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 19 2007

If p[1]=2, p[i]=3, (i>1), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j] = p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j] = -1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n >= 1, a(n-1) = det A. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 29 2010

A052927.name: Expansion of 1/(1-4*x-x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/3)} binomial(n-2*k, k)*4^(n-3*k). - _Paul Barry_, Oct 20 2004

A052928.name: The even numbers repeated.
formula: a(n) = n + Sum_{k=1..n} (-1)^k. - _William A. Tedeschi_, Mar 20 2008
For n > 0, a(n) = floor(sqrt(n^2+(-1)^n)). - _Francesco Daddi_, Aug 02 2011
a(n) = Sum_{k>=0} A030308(n,k)*b(k) with b(0)=0 and b(k)=2^k for k>0. - _Philippe Deléham_, Oct 19 2011
a(n) = n - (n mod 2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 29 2013
a(n) = a(a(n-1)) + a(n-a(n-1)) for n>2. - _Nathan Fox_, Jul 24 2016
a(b(n)) = b(n) + ((-1)^b(n) - 1)/2 for any sequence b(n) of offset 0.
a(n)*a(n+1)/2 = A007590(n), also equals partial sums of a(n).

A052931.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - 3*x^2 - x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(k, n-2k)3^(3k-n). - _Paul Barry_, Oct 04 2004

A052936.name: Expansion of (1-x)*(1-2*x)/(1-5*x+5*x^2).
formula: The sequence beginning 2, 7, 25 ... has g.f. (2-3*x)/(1-5*x+5*x^2), a(n) = (1-2/sqrt(5))*(5/2-sqrt(5)/2)^n + (5/2+sqrt(5)/2)^n*(1+2/sqrt(5)). It is the binomial transform of Fib(2*n+3) and the second binomial transform of Fib(n+3). Also, its n-th term is the n-th term of the 3rd binomial transform of Fib(3*n+3) divided by 2^n. - _Paul Barry_, Mar 23 2004
Binomial transform of convolution of Fib(2*n+1) and (-1)^n. Binomial transform of Fib(n+1)^2. - _Paul Barry_, Sep 27 2004
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} C(n-1, k)*Fib(2*n-2*k+1). - _Paul Barry_, Jun 07 2005
a(2*n) = 5^(n-1)*Lucas(2*n+2) for n>=1 with a(2*0)=1 and a(2*n+1) = 5^n * Fibonacci(2*n+3). - _G. C. Greubel_, Oct 18 2019

A052937.name: Expansion of (2-3*x-x^2)/((1-x)*(1-2*x-x^2)).
formula: a(n) = A000129(n+1) + 1, where A000129 are the Pell Numbers. - _Graeme McRae_, Aug 03 2006

A052940.name: a(0) = 1; a(n) = 3*2^n - 1, for n > 0.
formula: a(n) = A107909(A023548(n+1)) for n>1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, May 28 2005
Row sums of triangle A134060. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 05 2007
Equals row sums of triangle A140182. - _Gary W. Adamson_, May 11 2008
Equals M*Q, where M is a modified Pascal triangle (1,2) with first term "1" instead of 2; as an infinite lower triangular matrix. Q is the vector (1, 2, 2, 2, ...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 30 2015

A052942.name: Expansion of 1/((1+x)*(1-2*x+2*x^2-2*x^3)).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/3)} A128099(n-2*k, k). - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Aug 28 2013

A052944.name: a(n) = 2^n + n - 1.
formula: a(n+1) = 2*a(n) - n + 2 with a(0)=0. - Pieter Moree, Mar 06 2004
For n>=1: partial sums of A000051. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Mar 04 2004
a(0)=0, a(1)=2, a(2)=5, a(n+3) = 4*a(n+2) - 5*a(n+1) + 2*a(n). - Hermann Kremer (Hermann.Kremer(AT)online.de), Mar 16 2004
E.g.f.: U(0), where U(k) = 1 + x/(2^k + 2^k/(x - 1 - x^2*2^(k+1)/(x*2^(k+1) - (k+1)/U(k+1) )));(continued fraction, 3rd kind, 4-step ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 01 2012
G.f.: G(0)*x/(1-x) where G(k) = 1 + 2^k/(1 - x/(x + 2^k/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 24 2013
G.f.: Q(0)*x/(1-x), where Q(k)= 1 + 1/(2^k - 2*x*4^k/(2*x*2^k + 1/Q(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 24 2013

A052945.name: Number of compositions of n when each odd part can be of two kinds.
formula: First binomial transform of 2, 3, 6, 9, 18, 27, 54, 81, ... starting after 1. (End)

A052947.name: Expansion of 1/(1-x^2-2*x^3).
formula: If p[1]=0, p[2]=1, p[3]=2, p[i]=0, (i>3), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n-1)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 02 2010

A052948.name: Expansion of g.f.: (1-2*x)/(1-3*x+2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = (1 + (1+sqrt(3))^n + (1-sqrt(3))^n)/3. Binomial transform of A025192 (with interpolated zeros). - _Paul Barry_, Sep 16 2003

A052950.name: Expansion of (2-3*x-x^2+x^3)/((1-x)*(1+x)*(1-2*x)).
formula: a(2*n + 1) = 4 * a(2*n - 1) for all n in Z. a(2*n + 2) = 3*a(2*n + 1) + 2*a(2*n) if n>0. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 04 2014

A052951.name: Expansion of (1 + x - 2*x^2)/(1 - 2*x)^2.
formula: a(n) = A118413(n+1,n-1) for n > 2. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 27 2006

A052952.name: a(n) = Fibonacci(n+2) - (1-(-1)^n)/2.
formula: a(2*k) = Sum_{j=0..k} F(2*j+1) = F(2*(k+1)) for k >= 0; a(2*k-1) = Sum_{j=0..k} F(2*j) = F(2*k+1)-1 for k >= 1 (F = A000045, Fibonacci numbers).
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)) binomial(n-k+1, k). - _Paul Barry_, Oct 23 2004
a(n) = floor(phi^(n+2) / sqrt(5)), where phi is the golden ratio: phi = (1+sqrt(5))/2. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 19 2005
a(n) = Fibonacci(n+1) + a(n-2) with n>1, a(0)=a(1)=1. - _Zerinvary Lajos_, Mar 17 2008
a(n+1) = a(n) + a(n-1) + A059841(n+1). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 06 2012

a(n) = floor(|F((1+i)*(n+2))|), n >= 0, with the complex Fibonacci function F: C -> C, z -> F(z) with F(z) := (exp(log(phi)*z) - exp(i*Pi*z)*exp(-log(phi)*z))/(2*phi-1) with the modulus |z|, the imaginary unit i and the golden section phi:=(1+sqrt(5))/2. A Conjecture: For F(z) see, e.g., the T. Koshy reference. ch. 45, p. 523, where F is called f, given in A000045. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jul 24 2012
a(n) = floor(phi*Fibonacci(n+1)), where phi is the golden section. - _Michel Dekking_, Dec 02 2016
a(n) = -(-1)^n * a(-4-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 03 2016
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{i=0..n} C(n-k-1,k-i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 21 2017
a(n) = floor(1/(Sum_{k>=n+4} 1/Fibonacci(k))) [Ohtsuka and Nakamura]. - _Michel Marcus_, Aug 09 2018

A052954.name: Expansion of (2-x-x^2-x^3)/((1-x)*(1-x^2-x^3)).
formula: lim n->inf a(n)/a(n-1) = positive root of 1+x-x^3 (smallest Pisot-Vijayaraghavan number, A060006) - _Gerald McGarvey_, Sep 19 2004

A052955.name: a(2n) = 2*2^n - 1, a(2n+1) = 3*2^n - 1.
formula: a(n) = -1 + Sum_{alpha = RootOf(-1 + 2*Z^2)} (1/4) * (3 + 4*alpha) * alpha^(-1-n). (That is, the sum is indexed by the roots of the polynomial -1 + 2*Z^2.)
a(n) = 1 + Sum_{k=0..n-1} A016116(k). - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Jun 05 2004
a(n) = A027383(n-1) + 1 for n>0. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Sep 15 2007
a(n) = A132666(a(n-1)) + 1 for n>0. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Sep 15 2007
a(2n+1) = (a(2*n) + a(2*n+2))/2. Combined with a(n) = 2*a(n-2) + 1, n >= 2 and a(0) = 1, this specifies the sequence. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Nov 30 2013
a(n) = -(2^(n+1)) * A107659(-3-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 24 2018

A052959.name: a(2n) = a(2n-1)+a(2n-2), a(2n+1) = a(2n)+a(2n-1)-1, a(0)=2, a(1)=1.
formula: a(n) = Fibonacci(n+1) + (1+(-1)^n)/2 = A000045(n+1) + A059841(n). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 23 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} ( C(k, n-k) + (-1)^(n-k) ). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 21 2003

A052960.name: Expansion of ( 1-x-x^2 ) / ( 1-2*x-2*x^2+x^3+x^4 ).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n} Sum_{k=0..n/2} binomial(i+2*k, 2*k)*binomial(i+k, n-i-2*k). - _Emanuele Munarini_, May 10 2011

A052961.name: Expansion of (1 - 3*x) / (1 - 5*x + 3*x^2).
formula: E.g.f.: (1 + sqrt(13) + (sqrt(13)-1) * exp(sqrt(13)*x)) / (2*sqrt(13) * exp(((sqrt(13)-5)*x)/2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 16 2015

A052963.name: a(0)=1, a(1)=2, a(2)=5, a(n) = 3*a(n+2) - a(n+3).
formula: a(n)/a(n-1) tends to 2.8793852... = 1/(2*cos(4*Pi/9)), a root of x^3 -3x^2 + 1 (the characteristic polynomial of the 3 X 3 matrix). The latter polynomial is a factor (with (x + 1)) of the 4th degree polynomial of A066170: x^4 - 2x^3 - 3x^2 + x + 1. Given the 3 X 3 matrix [0 1 0 / 0 0 1 / -1 0 3], (M^n)*[1 1 1] = [a(n-2), a(n-1), a(n)]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Feb 29 2004

A052975.name: Expansion of (1-2*x)*(1-x)/(1-5*x+6*x^2-x^3).
formula: a(n) = 2^n*A(n;1/2)=(1/7)*(s(2)^2*c(4)^(2n) + s(4)^2*c(1)^(2n) + s(1)^2*c(2)^(2n)), where c(j):=2*cos(2Pi*j/7) and s(j):=2*Sin(2Pi*j/7). Here A(n;d), n in N, d in C denotes the respective quasi-Fibonacci number - see A121449 and Witula-Slota-Warzynski paper for details (see also A094789, A085810, A077998, A006054, A121442). I note that my and the respective Herbert Kociemba's formulas are "compatible". - _Roman Witula_, Aug 09 2012

A052977.name: Expansion of (1-x)(1+x)/(1 - x - x^2 - x^3 + x^5).

A052980.name: Expansion of (1 - x)/(1 - 2*x - x^3).
formula: Recurrence: a(0)=1, a(1)=1, a(2)=2; thereafter a(n) = 2*a(n-1)+a(n-3).
Let u1 = 2.20556943... denote the real root of x^3-2*x^2-1. There is an explicit constant c1 = 0.460719842... such that for n>0, a(n) = nearest integer to c1*u1^n. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Nov 07 2016
a(2n) = a(n)^2 - a(n-1)^2 + (1/2)*(a(n+2) - a(n+1) - a(n))^2. - _Greg Dresden_ and _Michael Tulskikh_, Aug 20 2019
a(n+1) = (Sum_{i >= 0} 2^(n-3i-2)*(4*binomial(n-2i, i) + binomial(n-2i-2, i))). - _Michael Tulskikh_, Feb 14 2020

A052983.name: Least multiple of n consisting of a succession of 1's followed by a succession of 0's.
formula: a(n) = A276348(n) * n; A227362(a(n)) = 10. - _Jaroslav Krizek_, Aug 30 2016

A052984.name: a(n) = 5*a(n-1) - 2*a(n-2) for n>1, with a(0) = 1, a(1) = 3.
formula: a(n) = [M^(n+1)]_2,2, where M is the 3 X 3 matrix defined as follows: M = [2,1,2; 1,1,1; 2,1,2]. - _Simone Severini_, Jun 12 2006
a(n-1) = Sum_{k=0..n} A147703(n,k)*(-1)^k*2^(n-k), n>1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 29 2008

A052991.name: Expansion of (1-x-x^2)/(1-3x-x^2).
formula: G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 + x^2 - (2*k+1)*x + x*(2*k-1 - x)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 05 2013

A052995.name: Expansion of 2*x*(1 - x)/(1 - 3*x + x^2).
formula: a(n) = 1/2*(F(2*n+8) mod F(2*n+2)) for n > 2. - _Gary Detlefs_, Nov 22 2010
a(n) = F(n-3)*F(n-1) + F(n)*F(n+2) for n > 0, F(-2) = -1, F(-1) = 1. - _Bruno Berselli_, Nov 03 2015
a(n) = (2^(-n)*((3 - sqrt(5))^n*(1 + sqrt(5)) + (-1 + sqrt(5))*(3 + sqrt(5))^n))/sqrt(5) for n > 0. - _Colin Barker_, Mar 30 2016
a(n) = Fibonacci(2*n-2) + Lucas(2*n-2) for n > 0. - _Bruno Berselli_, Oct 13 2017

A052997.name: Expansion of (1+x-x^3)/((1-2*x)*(1-x^2)).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1)+1 for even n, otherwise a(n) = 2*a(n-1), with a(0)=1, a(1)=3. [_Bruno Berselli_, Jun 19 2014]

A052999.name: Take n-th prime p, let P = all primes that can be obtained by permuting the digits of p and possibly adding or omitting zeros; a(n) = |p-q| where q in P is the closest to p but different from p (a(n)=0 if no such q exists).
